\@writefile{lot}{\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces $\lambda $ sweep comparing AmbGCE{} and TanGCE{} at fixed step sizes across three concept domains (Qwen2.5-0.5B, layer~8). NL: retrained nonlinear MLP probe accuracy (hidden 256, 1500 steps, AdamW lr=$10^{-3}$; same architecture used for HPO and evaluation) on the target concept (lower = stronger erasure). Both methods use the same GCE concept scorer (hidden 256, 1500 steps). AmbGCE{} becomes less effective at high $\lambda $ under the current protocol, while TanGCE{} continues improving. We interpret this as supportive evidence for the local manifold motivation of tangent-constrained updates, not as a complete characterization of the leakage-utility frontier. The expanded HPO grid $\{0.25,\ldots  ,32.0\}$ used in the multi-model experiments further tests this range. Bold: best NL per domain.}}{14}{table.caption.34}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{tab:lambda_sweep}{{5}{14}{$\lambda $ sweep comparing \AmbGCE {} and \TanGCE {} at fixed step sizes across three concept domains (Qwen2.5-0.5B, layer~8). NL: retrained nonlinear MLP probe accuracy (hidden 256, 1500 steps, AdamW lr=$10^{-3}$; same architecture used for HPO and evaluation) on the target concept (lower = stronger erasure). Both methods use the same GCE concept scorer (hidden 256, 1500 steps). \AmbGCE {} becomes less effective at high $\lambda $ under the current protocol, while \TanGCE {} continues improving. We interpret this as supportive evidence for the local manifold motivation of tangent-constrained updates, not as a complete characterization of the leakage-utility frontier. The expanded HPO grid $\{0.25,\ldots ,32.0\}$ used in the multi-model experiments further tests this range. Bold: best NL per domain}{table.caption.34}{}}
